         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>a. It is not certain whether there are any
significant traces after l.6.</p>
            <p>b. In l.11 the missing area may well have been an
original fault, since the surviving letters convey all the information
that we would expect.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <ab>a. In the reign of
Justinian, the seventh indiction, the first month <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
            </ab>
            <ab>b. Here earth covers the
sacred head of a girl who, before, had an appropriate name. She was of
well-famed skill and similarly of a seemly reputation, being always
(engaged) in prudent labours. But, Euphemia, may you come to the choir
of the blessed gods. Euphemia completed her life at 18 years, in the
<supplied reason="lost">seventh</supplied> indiction <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/> the first month.</ab>
         </div>
